The command \(is.na()\) returns to the logical output of the data missing: if the data is missing, it will returns to \(TRUE\), otherwise \(False\). The function \(sum()\) will make a summation, which will returns a numerical output with the function \(is.na()\) inside, shows how many missing data. In this command, the \(apply()\) function will apply \(sum()\) to each column to count the number of missing data for each column.

iv.

Two methods. First we can write a nested-loop to remove the rows which contains a missing data.

index_ls = c()
for(i in 1:dim(housing)[1]){
  for(j in 1:dim(housing)[2]){
    check <- is.na(housing[i,j])
    if(check == TRUE){
      index_ls = c(index_ls, i)
      break
    }
  }
}
housing <- housing[-index_ls,]
dim(housing)
## [1] 630  22

Or we can use the function \(na.omit()\) to filting the row does not contains a missing data.

housing <- na.omit(housing)
dim(housing)
## [1] 630  22
v.
num_rm <- row_or[1] - dim(housing)[1]
num_rm
## [1] 1876

From \(iii.\), the data that missing most are in \(REACNumber\), which is 1873. It is closed to the number of rows we romoved. So this result seems reasonable.

vii.
logUnit <- log(housing[, "UnitCount"])

viii.
after1950 <- c()
for(i in 1:dim(housing)[1]){
  if(housing[i,"YearBuilt"] >= 1950){
    after1950 <- c(after1950, TRUE)
  }
  else{
    after1950 <- c(after1950, FALSE)
  }
}
housing$after1950 <- after1950
head(housing$after1950)
## [1] FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE  TRUE
